WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:01.969 --> 00:00:04.260
FEMALE SPEAKER: Jessica is
an entrepreneur and investor

00:00:04.260 --> 00:00:06.820
focused on financial
inclusion, the sharing

00:00:06.820 --> 00:00:09.260
economy, and social justice.

00:00:09.260 --> 00:00:11.840
She's best known as
a co-founder of Kiva,

00:00:11.840 --> 00:00:15.680
the world's people-the-people
microlending website.

00:00:15.680 --> 00:00:17.470
In her new book,
"Clay Water Brick"

00:00:17.470 --> 00:00:19.460
that she's going to
share about today,

00:00:19.460 --> 00:00:21.510
she shares her personal
story of co-creating

00:00:21.510 --> 00:00:25.310
a tool for social change and
the evolution of this nonprofit

00:00:25.310 --> 00:00:28.250
that started in a modest
off-campus Stanford apartment,

00:00:28.250 --> 00:00:30.660
and went on to be
a global movement.

00:00:30.660 --> 00:00:33.190
Jessica highlights
the life lessons

00:00:33.190 --> 00:00:35.900
she's learned firsthand from
the entrepreneurs themselves,

00:00:35.900 --> 00:00:38.220
many of them in the
world's poorest countries.

00:00:38.220 --> 00:00:40.680
So I'm going to leave
no further introduction,

00:00:40.680 --> 00:00:43.597
and have Jessica share
her story with us.

00:00:43.597 --> 00:00:46.579
[APPLAUSE]

00:00:49.380 --> 00:00:50.880
JESSICA JACKLEY:
Thank you very much

00:00:50.880 --> 00:00:52.360
for the very kind introduction.

00:00:52.360 --> 00:00:54.220
Thank you all for being here.

00:00:54.220 --> 00:00:57.292
I'm touched, and I don't
take the time that you're

00:00:57.292 --> 00:00:58.500
spending hear me for granted.

00:00:58.500 --> 00:01:00.397
So we dive right
in, and by the way,

00:01:00.397 --> 00:01:02.730
there's a little squeaky baby
in the back and he's mine,

00:01:02.730 --> 00:01:04.142
and I'm happy he's here.

00:01:04.142 --> 00:01:08.080
He probably will want to
chime in a little bit.

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:10.080
I'm going to first talk
to you about a gentleman

00:01:10.080 --> 00:01:11.760
that I met 10 years
ago named Patrick.

00:01:11.760 --> 00:01:14.545
I met him in Uganda, in a
little village on the border

00:01:14.545 --> 00:01:16.470
of Kenya and Uganda.

00:01:16.470 --> 00:01:19.497
He had fled the northern
area of the country years

00:01:19.497 --> 00:01:21.830
earlier, because a rebel group
had attacked his village,

00:01:21.830 --> 00:01:24.910
and he fled only with his
brother and nothing else.

00:01:24.910 --> 00:01:27.750
No shoes on his feet, just
the clothes on his back.

00:01:27.750 --> 00:01:30.790
He was young,
uneducated, orphaned,

00:01:30.790 --> 00:01:31.957
and really didn't have much.

00:01:31.957 --> 00:01:33.331
And I think a lot
of people would

00:01:33.331 --> 00:01:35.110
have looked at Patrick's
life and thought,

00:01:35.110 --> 00:01:37.970
the situation is hopeless,
this person is hopeless.

00:01:37.970 --> 00:01:40.050
But Patrick didn't believe that.

00:01:40.050 --> 00:01:43.560
He knew that he had
within themselves

00:01:43.560 --> 00:01:47.200
what it took to improve his
life and to lift himself up out

00:01:47.200 --> 00:01:47.700
of poverty.

00:01:47.700 --> 00:01:50.460
And so one day, as he
described the story to me,

00:01:50.460 --> 00:01:53.290
he was sitting, kind of leaning
against the mud structure

00:01:53.290 --> 00:01:55.505
where he and his
brother slept, and he

00:01:55.505 --> 00:01:58.110
was thinking, as he did every
day, about what his plan was

00:01:58.110 --> 00:02:00.350
going to be to feed
himself and his brother.

00:02:00.350 --> 00:02:02.450
And he sort of had
this aha moment.

00:02:02.450 --> 00:02:05.900
He kind of looked down where
his hand was touching the earth

00:02:05.900 --> 00:02:07.620
and he began to dig.

00:02:07.620 --> 00:02:13.300
And at first, when he dug,
he didn't discover too much,

00:02:13.300 --> 00:02:15.810
but he got a piece of
wood and a scrap of metal,

00:02:15.810 --> 00:02:17.760
and started to kind
of use these homemade

00:02:17.760 --> 00:02:20.190
implements to dig deeper,
and he found clay deposits.

00:02:20.190 --> 00:02:22.920
And he learned, as
he dug, that if he

00:02:22.920 --> 00:02:25.650
mixed a little bit of water with
that clay, it could be shaped.

00:02:25.650 --> 00:02:28.729
And so he created these bricks,
just with his own two hands.

00:02:28.729 --> 00:02:30.770
The first bricks were
really rough and misshapen,

00:02:30.770 --> 00:02:33.150
and kind of crumbled
easily, but he kept at it.

00:02:33.150 --> 00:02:34.710
He got better and
better, and soon he

00:02:34.710 --> 00:02:37.179
made bricks that were good
enough, high quality enough,

00:02:37.179 --> 00:02:37.970
to be able to sell.

00:02:37.970 --> 00:02:39.428
Just for fractions
of a penny each,

00:02:39.428 --> 00:02:41.280
but it was enough
to get started.

00:02:41.280 --> 00:02:42.570
So he did that.

00:02:42.570 --> 00:02:45.924
Sold those bricks and saved up.

00:02:45.924 --> 00:02:47.340
And eventually,
he was able to buy

00:02:47.340 --> 00:02:50.661
a brick mould, which instantly
doubled his production.

00:02:50.661 --> 00:02:52.160
He was able to make
bricks that were

00:02:52.160 --> 00:02:55.760
more smoothly and
consistently shaped and sized.

00:02:55.760 --> 00:02:57.530
And he dried those
bricks in the sun,

00:02:57.530 --> 00:02:58.790
because that's what was free.

00:02:58.790 --> 00:03:00.040
That's what he knew how to do.

00:03:00.040 --> 00:03:02.540
And those bricks sold
for a little bit more

00:03:02.540 --> 00:03:05.414
than the other ones that
he had just made by hand.

00:03:05.414 --> 00:03:06.580
You can see where this goes.

00:03:06.580 --> 00:03:08.030
He continued to save up money.

00:03:08.030 --> 00:03:10.080
He knew that if he baked
the bricks in a kiln,

00:03:10.080 --> 00:03:11.120
they would sell for even more.

00:03:11.120 --> 00:03:12.870
So of course, he saved
up to be able to go

00:03:12.870 --> 00:03:15.425
to a neighboring village and to
learn, and kind of apprentice

00:03:15.425 --> 00:03:17.050
for a little while,
with the brickmaker

00:03:17.050 --> 00:03:19.470
there and learn how to
make a self-contained kiln.

00:03:19.470 --> 00:03:21.550
So he did that, baked the
bricks, and of course,

00:03:21.550 --> 00:03:23.547
those sold for more.

00:03:23.547 --> 00:03:25.130
And eventually, he
was able to replace

00:03:25.130 --> 00:03:27.580
those homemade implements
with a shovel, and a trowel,

00:03:27.580 --> 00:03:31.540
and other things to be much more
of an official business person,

00:03:31.540 --> 00:03:32.477
as a brickmaker.

00:03:32.477 --> 00:03:35.060
He was able to hire his brother,
and then a neighbor, and then

00:03:35.060 --> 00:03:37.010
another, and by the
time I met Patrick,

00:03:37.010 --> 00:03:39.710
he had this booming business,
was doing quite well,

00:03:39.710 --> 00:03:41.440
and was a real leader
in his community.

00:03:41.440 --> 00:03:44.060
And perhaps, at least
to me, most notably,

00:03:44.060 --> 00:03:47.010
he showed me were sort of
this epiphany had happened,

00:03:47.010 --> 00:03:48.594
and also showed me
the home next to it

00:03:48.594 --> 00:03:49.885
that he had built the new home.

00:03:49.885 --> 00:03:51.550
Not just the old
packed mud home,

00:03:51.550 --> 00:03:53.160
but the new one with
baked mud bricks

00:03:53.160 --> 00:03:57.740
that he had pulled from the
earth with his own two hands.

00:03:57.740 --> 00:04:00.110
If that's not entrepreneurial,
I'm not sure what it is.

00:04:00.110 --> 00:04:00.990
That's Patrick.

00:04:00.990 --> 00:04:04.330
The second story I'll
tell you is of Fatuma.

00:04:04.330 --> 00:04:07.590
Now Fatuma, I met
about 700 miles-ish

00:04:07.590 --> 00:04:09.920
due south of where
I met Patrick.

00:04:09.920 --> 00:04:12.540
Fatuma lived in a village
outside of Dodoma, Tanzania,

00:04:12.540 --> 00:04:15.410
and she was also
an entrepreneur.

00:04:15.410 --> 00:04:18.660
But her story ended a little bit
differently than Patrick's had.

00:04:18.660 --> 00:04:22.997
So to kind of tell you why I
was there in the first place,

00:04:22.997 --> 00:04:25.580
I was working for several months
with a nonprofit organization

00:04:25.580 --> 00:04:28.050
called Village Enterprise, a
great bay area nonprofit that

00:04:28.050 --> 00:04:30.930
provided, at the time,
microgrants of $100

00:04:30.930 --> 00:04:33.400
to entrepreneurs so
they could start or grow

00:04:33.400 --> 00:04:36.046
their simple businesses.

00:04:36.046 --> 00:04:38.170
Patrick and Fatuma were
two of these entrepreneurs,

00:04:38.170 --> 00:04:40.100
and I was there sort of
surveying them, interviewing

00:04:40.100 --> 00:04:41.880
them, asking them, did
you receive the money?

00:04:41.880 --> 00:04:43.046
If you did, how did it work?

00:04:43.046 --> 00:04:45.279
Did it change the trajectory
of your business at all?

00:04:45.279 --> 00:04:46.320
Did it improve your life?

00:04:46.320 --> 00:04:46.820
How so?

00:04:46.820 --> 00:04:49.157
And I was doing this sort
of standard of living survey

00:04:49.157 --> 00:04:51.365
and had a questionnaire that
I would ask entrepreneur

00:04:51.365 --> 00:04:52.170
after entrepreneur.

00:04:52.170 --> 00:04:55.215
So these are just two of
the 150-ish entrepreneurs

00:04:55.215 --> 00:04:58.780
I met during that period
of time, 10 years ago.

00:04:58.780 --> 00:05:00.780
Fatuma kind of pulled
me into her home,

00:05:00.780 --> 00:05:03.831
and who here has been
inside of a mud hut before?

00:05:03.831 --> 00:05:04.830
I'm going to guess some.

00:05:04.830 --> 00:05:05.371
There you go.

00:05:05.371 --> 00:05:07.730
So I think they're
totally fascinating.

00:05:07.730 --> 00:05:10.220
I am sure that I could
never build one myself,

00:05:10.220 --> 00:05:13.684
but I kind of really love
looking at the structures.

00:05:13.684 --> 00:05:15.100
So this is not
actually-- I didn't

00:05:15.100 --> 00:05:16.650
get pictures of her and
her home at the time,

00:05:16.650 --> 00:05:17.970
but this is not
actually her home.

00:05:17.970 --> 00:05:20.136
And it looked a little bit
like this on the outside,

00:05:20.136 --> 00:05:23.352
and on the inside, some of
the nicest homes like this

00:05:23.352 --> 00:05:24.810
that I've been in
looked like this.

00:05:24.810 --> 00:05:29.300
With actual furniture,
different implements,

00:05:29.300 --> 00:05:31.490
quite a nice
brightly lit inside.

00:05:31.490 --> 00:05:33.780
But Fatuma's looked
a lot more like this

00:05:33.780 --> 00:05:35.540
So imagine, she pulls
me in, sits me down

00:05:35.540 --> 00:05:38.060
in one of the few pieces
of furniture in her home.

00:05:38.060 --> 00:05:40.450
There was two folding chairs
and a little table, and then

00:05:40.450 --> 00:05:43.540
the mattress where she's slept,
and that was pretty much it.

00:05:43.540 --> 00:05:45.082
So she pulled me
in, sat down, and we

00:05:45.082 --> 00:05:47.415
started to talk about her
business, which was a charcoal

00:05:47.415 --> 00:05:48.182
selling business.

00:05:48.182 --> 00:05:50.140
And she showed me the
records that she had kept

00:05:50.140 --> 00:05:51.420
in these little blue books.

00:05:51.420 --> 00:05:54.530
Now, does anyone have a visceral
memory when I talk about this?

00:05:54.530 --> 00:05:55.890
Blue books.

00:05:55.890 --> 00:05:56.800
Right?

00:05:56.800 --> 00:05:59.300
Like the things, that least I
used to write my middle school

00:05:59.300 --> 00:06:00.133
essays in and stuff.

00:06:00.133 --> 00:06:01.280
So she had blue books.

00:06:01.280 --> 00:06:02.410
Kind of funny.

00:06:02.410 --> 00:06:06.280
And kept her records in there,
and as we went through them,

00:06:06.280 --> 00:06:09.460
I got really excited,
because her business was

00:06:09.460 --> 00:06:12.510
doing much better than a lot
of the businesses I had seen,

00:06:12.510 --> 00:06:14.210
even those that were
quite successful.

00:06:14.210 --> 00:06:16.209
And I thought I had
discovered this sort of rags

00:06:16.209 --> 00:06:16.900
to riches story.

00:06:16.900 --> 00:06:19.164
I got really excited, I
double-checked her numbers,

00:06:19.164 --> 00:06:21.580
looked, not only at that little
blue book full of records,

00:06:21.580 --> 00:06:22.204
but other ones.

00:06:22.204 --> 00:06:26.090
And in fact, her numbers
panned out, they were correct.

00:06:26.090 --> 00:06:28.355
But I was baffled
because as I asked her

00:06:28.355 --> 00:06:30.980
the kind of questions that I had
been asking many entrepreneurs

00:06:30.980 --> 00:06:33.384
up until that point, like,
how have you reinvested

00:06:33.384 --> 00:06:35.550
the profits of your business
back into the business,

00:06:35.550 --> 00:06:37.258
or how have you improved
your life thanks

00:06:37.258 --> 00:06:39.460
to these new profits?

00:06:39.460 --> 00:06:41.975
I didn't see
anything that told me

00:06:41.975 --> 00:06:43.350
that she was
actually reinvesting

00:06:43.350 --> 00:06:44.430
in herself or in her family.

00:06:44.430 --> 00:06:45.960
Her clothes were
tattered, her shoes

00:06:45.960 --> 00:06:47.390
were kind of falling apart.

00:06:47.390 --> 00:06:51.930
She was very gaunt, barely
ate three meals a day.

00:06:51.930 --> 00:06:54.034
And basically, there was
nothing that I could see,

00:06:54.034 --> 00:06:55.700
no signs of newfound
wealth in her home.

00:06:55.700 --> 00:06:59.050
So I asked her directly
and she said things like,

00:06:59.050 --> 00:07:03.090
oh, it's fine, you
know, my days will pass.

00:07:03.090 --> 00:07:03.780
I am OK.

00:07:03.780 --> 00:07:07.260
She was very, content is
not quite the right word,

00:07:07.260 --> 00:07:10.540
but she had no dreams to
do anything with her money.

00:07:10.540 --> 00:07:13.580
And I pushed her on it
and I said, OK, fine,

00:07:13.580 --> 00:07:16.069
but where actually did
you put all this money,

00:07:16.069 --> 00:07:17.860
because you should have
kind of a nice pile

00:07:17.860 --> 00:07:19.980
somewhere if what you're
telling me is correct?

00:07:19.980 --> 00:07:21.860
And she was kind of a joker.

00:07:21.860 --> 00:07:25.450
She kind of looked around
as if anyone else was there,

00:07:25.450 --> 00:07:27.800
and like tiptoed over to
the far side of her hut

00:07:27.800 --> 00:07:31.890
and patted the ground, and she
said, it's in the world bank.

00:07:31.890 --> 00:07:32.925
Which was kind of funny.

00:07:32.925 --> 00:07:34.670
I mean, you don't
get a lot of jokes

00:07:34.670 --> 00:07:36.430
when you're looking
at, you know,

00:07:36.430 --> 00:07:38.075
very impoverished situations.

00:07:38.075 --> 00:07:39.950
There's not a lot of
poverty jokes out there.

00:07:39.950 --> 00:07:41.900
But she thought
that was so funny.

00:07:41.900 --> 00:07:42.964
I laughed, it was funny.

00:07:42.964 --> 00:07:44.380
She had literally
buried her money

00:07:44.380 --> 00:07:48.569
in the grounds, in the earth
floor next to where she slept.

00:07:48.569 --> 00:07:49.860
That's what made her feel safe.

00:07:49.860 --> 00:07:52.520
That's what made her feel good.

00:07:52.520 --> 00:07:54.440
She didn't have real
dreams for the future

00:07:54.440 --> 00:07:56.270
and she certainly
hadn't reinvested

00:07:56.270 --> 00:08:01.090
much at all back into her
life to make things better.

00:08:01.090 --> 00:08:02.770
Every other
entrepreneur that I met

00:08:02.770 --> 00:08:04.900
did have that,
almost all of them.

00:08:04.900 --> 00:08:07.010
They had these amazing
dreams for the future

00:08:07.010 --> 00:08:09.251
and I have a long list of
things that I heard about

00:08:09.251 --> 00:08:11.750
as I asked individuals, not
only what they had done already.

00:08:11.750 --> 00:08:13.458
You know, send their
daughters to school,

00:08:13.458 --> 00:08:15.450
afford three meals a
day, buy a mosquito net,

00:08:15.450 --> 00:08:16.580
all sorts of things.

00:08:16.580 --> 00:08:18.370
They had many other
dreams for the future.

00:08:18.370 --> 00:08:21.140
You know, travels to faraway
places, new clothing,

00:08:21.140 --> 00:08:25.610
shiny electronics, education
for all of their children,

00:08:25.610 --> 00:08:26.390
and on and on.

00:08:26.390 --> 00:08:28.200
But Fatima did not.

00:08:28.200 --> 00:08:31.560
And since that day, I've sort
of been fascinated by a number

00:08:31.560 --> 00:08:34.240
things, but especially,
I've been fascinated

00:08:34.240 --> 00:08:37.620
by this question, what makes
some people dig, and find

00:08:37.620 --> 00:08:40.346
opportunity literally in the
ground beneath their feet,

00:08:40.346 --> 00:08:42.720
and what makes some people
bury the gifts that they have,

00:08:42.720 --> 00:08:44.800
the treasures that they do that?

00:08:44.800 --> 00:08:46.620
I don't think that
the answer to that

00:08:46.620 --> 00:08:49.000
is unrelated to
entrepreneurship.

00:08:49.000 --> 00:08:50.960
I do believe Fatuma
was an entrepreneur,

00:08:50.960 --> 00:08:53.750
but I think the main
difference between her

00:08:53.750 --> 00:08:55.730
and Patrick and the
many, many others

00:08:55.730 --> 00:08:58.600
like Patrick who had really
just big dreams what was next.

00:08:58.600 --> 00:09:00.490
I think the main
difference between them

00:09:00.490 --> 00:09:02.960
was that Patrick was able to
imagine a different future.

00:09:02.960 --> 00:09:06.300
He had a very strong vision
for what was out there for him.

00:09:06.300 --> 00:09:08.204
What could make his life
better and the lives

00:09:08.204 --> 00:09:09.370
of people around him better.

00:09:09.370 --> 00:09:11.430
He had this vision and
he wasn't afraid to keep

00:09:11.430 --> 00:09:13.390
pursuing that vision,
along the path,

00:09:13.390 --> 00:09:15.320
even when it got difficult.

00:09:15.320 --> 00:09:17.860
I think this has to do with
entrepreneurship, at least

00:09:17.860 --> 00:09:20.940
in some way, because
it speaks to,

00:09:20.940 --> 00:09:23.460
at least my favorite
definition of entrepreneurship,

00:09:23.460 --> 00:09:26.612
my favorite academic definition,
which is Howard Stevenson's

00:09:26.612 --> 00:09:27.820
from Harvard Business School.

00:09:27.820 --> 00:09:31.240
He says that entrepreneurship
is the pursuit of opportunity,

00:09:31.240 --> 00:09:33.920
without regard to resources
currently controlled.

00:09:33.920 --> 00:09:35.920
And maybe I'm reading
into it too much,

00:09:35.920 --> 00:09:37.770
but I think it's
quite a romantic idea.

00:09:37.770 --> 00:09:39.790
That the pursuit of
the thing that you

00:09:39.790 --> 00:09:42.040
vision in the future, the
pursuit of this opportunity

00:09:42.040 --> 00:09:44.130
that you see to
make things better,

00:09:44.130 --> 00:09:46.530
without regard to what
you might currently

00:09:46.530 --> 00:09:47.530
have in your possession.

00:09:47.530 --> 00:09:49.350
So it's about this
movement forward.

00:09:49.350 --> 00:09:53.570
Not what you own, not your
education or your pedigree,

00:09:53.570 --> 00:09:55.710
not a pile of resources
you might have at hand,

00:09:55.710 --> 00:09:56.640
at your network.

00:09:56.640 --> 00:09:59.052
Just going after this
thing and knowing

00:09:59.052 --> 00:10:01.010
that as you do that,
you'll find what you need,

00:10:01.010 --> 00:10:02.560
you'll make your way
over, around, and through.

00:10:02.560 --> 00:10:04.660
And I think the best
entrepreneurs that I've met

00:10:04.660 --> 00:10:07.300
are able to do that, because
they have this strong vision

00:10:07.300 --> 00:10:10.200
and they know that it's worth
it to keep moving forward.

