OK, so I want to now
digress a little bit.

00:10:15.990 --> 00:10:18.630
You might ask, then, at
least I do, OK, great.

00:10:18.630 --> 00:10:20.997
So if the thing that made
Patrick and others so great

00:10:20.997 --> 00:10:22.830
is that they had this
vision for the future,

00:10:22.830 --> 00:10:24.329
they were be able
to tell themselves

00:10:24.329 --> 00:10:27.360
a story for what could be
different in the future,

00:10:27.360 --> 00:10:28.860
why don't some people do that?

00:10:28.860 --> 00:10:30.920
Why did Fatima get stuck?

00:10:30.920 --> 00:10:31.810
And others like her?

00:10:31.810 --> 00:10:33.010
And why do we?

00:10:33.010 --> 00:10:34.637
With everything
we need around us,

00:10:34.637 --> 00:10:36.220
why do we get stuck
sometimes and feel

00:10:36.220 --> 00:10:37.740
like we can't move forward?

00:10:37.740 --> 00:10:41.837
I think it's because we end up
believing in the wrong stories.

00:10:41.837 --> 00:10:43.920
And so I think it's really
important to figure out

00:10:43.920 --> 00:10:46.170
what we're hearing and
believe the right ones,

00:10:46.170 --> 00:10:49.360
champion the right ones, retell,
perpetuate the better stories

00:10:49.360 --> 00:10:51.450
in the world that really
focus on potential,

00:10:51.450 --> 00:10:53.400
and not get stuck in
the wrong stories.

00:10:53.400 --> 00:10:56.210
Now, I know that that's what
I've had to do in my own life,

00:10:56.210 --> 00:10:59.610
and to briefly tell
you my own story,

00:10:59.610 --> 00:11:01.130
we're going to go way back.

00:11:01.130 --> 00:11:03.930
When I was five, I
was in Sunday school,

00:11:03.930 --> 00:11:06.220
and I'm not trying
to make fun, I just

00:11:06.220 --> 00:11:08.510
think this is how I saw
the world at five, right?

00:11:08.510 --> 00:11:10.340
This is Jesus, my buddy.

00:11:10.340 --> 00:11:13.130
I'm there on the
left, just kidding.

00:11:13.130 --> 00:11:17.560
But I just, you know, I had
a very simple world view,

00:11:17.560 --> 00:11:19.415
as I think a lot of
us do at five and six.

00:11:19.415 --> 00:11:21.040
And I remember the
first time I learned

00:11:21.040 --> 00:11:22.831
about poverty was in
a Sunday school class,

00:11:22.831 --> 00:11:25.700
sitting on the floor, hearing
my lovely Sunday school

00:11:25.700 --> 00:11:28.910
teacher, who I know had great
intentions, sort of haphazardly

00:11:28.910 --> 00:11:30.930
throw out different
things that were

00:11:30.930 --> 00:11:32.270
in the Bible about poverty.

00:11:32.270 --> 00:11:34.729
One thing she threw
out to us was this idea

00:11:34.729 --> 00:11:37.020
that Jesus told us, what you
do for the least of these,

00:11:37.020 --> 00:11:38.400
you do for me.

00:11:38.400 --> 00:11:41.780
And I remember hearing that, and
as a kid it might sound silly,

00:11:41.780 --> 00:11:43.560
but as kid, it was
deeply motivating

00:11:43.560 --> 00:11:45.060
and it was kind of
the closest thing

00:11:45.060 --> 00:11:47.000
that I had ever
felt to a calling.

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:49.180
I thought, wait
a minute, so if I

00:11:49.180 --> 00:11:51.760
help people that are in
need, if I helped the poor,

00:11:51.760 --> 00:11:53.230
then I'm doing
something for God?

00:11:53.230 --> 00:11:53.990
This is amazing.

00:11:53.990 --> 00:11:56.240
This is like the world's
greatest homework assignment.

00:11:56.240 --> 00:11:58.005
I'm going to go do that.

00:11:58.005 --> 00:11:58.560
Let's go.

00:11:58.560 --> 00:12:02.360
I was super motivated by this
idea that my life could matter.

00:12:02.360 --> 00:12:04.680
That I could do
something important--

00:12:04.680 --> 00:12:06.090
of cosmic importance, right?

00:12:06.090 --> 00:12:09.320
In the lives of other people.

00:12:09.320 --> 00:12:11.770
At the same time, she also
threw things out like this,

00:12:11.770 --> 00:12:15.366
and the second thing
that she threw out

00:12:15.366 --> 00:12:17.240
did not give me that
same sort of motivation.

00:12:17.240 --> 00:12:19.202
In fact, it scared
the pants off me.

00:12:19.202 --> 00:12:21.660
She also told us that Jesus
said that the poor would always

00:12:21.660 --> 00:12:24.140
be with us.

00:12:24.140 --> 00:12:26.910
I pictured in my head, as a
little kid, this long line

00:12:26.910 --> 00:12:29.720
of people that would always
be following me around, always

00:12:29.720 --> 00:12:32.629
with me, asking me for my
stuff and asking me to share.

00:12:32.629 --> 00:12:34.920
And while I wouldn't have
used language like, you know,

00:12:34.920 --> 00:12:35.836
this is unsustainable.

00:12:35.836 --> 00:12:38.140
I knew that, like, I
would run out of stuff.

00:12:38.140 --> 00:12:41.410
I only had so many crayons
that I could give out.

00:12:41.410 --> 00:12:43.030
I knew that this
wasn't going to work,

00:12:43.030 --> 00:12:46.810
and so I felt frustrated,
and in fact, angry, at god.

00:12:46.810 --> 00:12:49.429
At the world, for if
this was the reality.

00:12:49.429 --> 00:12:51.470
I felt like I'd been given
this great assignment,

00:12:51.470 --> 00:12:53.680
this great charge, this
great mission for my life.

00:12:53.680 --> 00:12:56.080
But I was being told in
advance I would totally fail,

00:12:56.080 --> 00:12:58.650
and I was angry.

00:12:58.650 --> 00:13:01.570
Unfortunately, a lot of the
stories I heard over the years

00:13:01.570 --> 00:13:05.290
after that little glimpse
when I was five-years-old

00:13:05.290 --> 00:13:08.830
felt and sounded and
looked a lot like this.

00:13:08.830 --> 00:13:11.240
They were stories focused
on sadness, and suffering,

00:13:11.240 --> 00:13:13.640
and desperation,
and hopelessness,

00:13:13.640 --> 00:13:15.111
often carefully crafted.

00:13:15.111 --> 00:13:16.610
These stories were
carefully crafted

00:13:16.610 --> 00:13:18.960
by well intentioned
nonprofits and NGOs that

00:13:18.960 --> 00:13:21.300
wanted me to feel something.

00:13:21.300 --> 00:13:25.630
I mean, the feelings that I felt
were panic, I felt overwhelmed,

00:13:25.630 --> 00:13:28.850
I felt quite guilty,
and I felt even

00:13:28.850 --> 00:13:31.930
shameful about my own relative
middle class American wealth.

00:13:31.930 --> 00:13:34.180
But I felt bad enough that
I whipped out my own money

00:13:34.180 --> 00:13:36.721
and gave whenever I could,
even as a kid and a teenager,

00:13:36.721 --> 00:13:37.220
whatever.

00:13:37.220 --> 00:13:40.410
And I called the 1-800
number and sponsored kids,

00:13:40.410 --> 00:13:43.127
and I hear that there
is a Christina Aguilera

00:13:43.127 --> 00:13:44.210
version of this right now.

00:13:44.210 --> 00:13:46.760
I should totally probably
update this, but in my day,

00:13:46.760 --> 00:13:49.320
this was Sally
Struthers all the way.

00:13:49.320 --> 00:13:51.710
I saw a lot of Sally growing up.

00:13:51.710 --> 00:13:54.670
So I responded, but mostly, if
I'm really honest with myself,

00:13:54.670 --> 00:13:56.360
I did so in a very
transactional way.

00:13:56.360 --> 00:13:58.920
I did so because
I was feeling bad,

00:13:58.920 --> 00:14:01.930
I was feeling like crap
about my own lack of ability

00:14:01.930 --> 00:14:05.290
to ever solve these problems,
no matter how much I did.

00:14:05.290 --> 00:14:08.290
And this yearning that I had
had a little kid to really

00:14:08.290 --> 00:14:09.920
be meaningful to
someone else had

00:14:09.920 --> 00:14:12.972
turned into this transaction,
not an interaction.

00:14:12.972 --> 00:14:14.430
A meaningful,
beautiful connection.

00:14:14.430 --> 00:14:17.340
It turned in to sort of
throw my change in the jar,

00:14:17.340 --> 00:14:20.100
temporarily feel a little
bit better about myself,

00:14:20.100 --> 00:14:22.750
and then go on with
the rest of my life.

00:14:22.750 --> 00:14:24.590
Until the next sad
story came along.

00:14:24.590 --> 00:14:26.730
And unfortunately,
what this did was

00:14:26.730 --> 00:14:29.890
lead to a sort of invisible
barrier being erected

00:14:29.890 --> 00:14:31.670
between myself
and these stories,

00:14:31.670 --> 00:14:33.440
and really, these
other people that I

00:14:33.440 --> 00:14:35.930
had very much
otherized and very much

00:14:35.930 --> 00:14:40.260
put in this category of not me.

00:14:40.260 --> 00:14:41.492
So don't worry.

00:14:41.492 --> 00:14:43.950
This is the saddest moment,
there's a lot of serious faces.

00:14:43.950 --> 00:14:45.250
Now it gets happier, ready?

00:14:45.250 --> 00:14:46.070
So here we go.

00:14:46.070 --> 00:14:50.930
So this was at its worst, how
I interacted with the poor.

00:14:50.930 --> 00:14:53.630
Lot of air quotes today.

00:14:53.630 --> 00:14:56.730
And then, and I'm really glad
I'm not talking to a college

00:14:56.730 --> 00:14:58.410
audience right now, because
I have to do a lot of caveats

00:14:58.410 --> 00:14:59.460
with them and say,
hey, look, I'm

00:14:59.460 --> 00:15:00.626
not prescribing you do this.

00:15:00.626 --> 00:15:02.600
Like, don't blame
me if you do this,

00:15:02.600 --> 00:15:05.940
but I studied philosophy and
poetry and then I, on a whim,

00:15:05.940 --> 00:15:06.995
moved out to California.

00:15:06.995 --> 00:15:09.120
I told my parents-- it was
right after graduation--

00:15:09.120 --> 00:15:10.953
and I told them I'd be
here for a few weeks.

00:15:10.953 --> 00:15:12.440
That was 15 years ago.

00:15:12.440 --> 00:15:15.980
So I moved out and I got a temp
job at the Stanford Business

00:15:15.980 --> 00:15:17.940
School, which it
first, by the way,

00:15:17.940 --> 00:15:20.010
I was kind of a hater
about business early on.

00:15:20.010 --> 00:15:22.380
I thought, no, I want
to be a part of things

00:15:22.380 --> 00:15:23.580
that help people.

00:15:23.580 --> 00:15:26.120
Nonprofits seemed to be helping
people, just go with me.

00:15:26.120 --> 00:15:29.104
For-profits must be bad,
so they are the enemies

00:15:29.104 --> 00:15:30.520
and here I was,
right in the heart

00:15:30.520 --> 00:15:32.595
of, like, enemy territory.

00:15:32.595 --> 00:15:34.220
This heart of
entrepreneurial activity,

00:15:34.220 --> 00:15:36.761
because I thought entrepreneurs
are the gang leaders of this,

00:15:36.761 --> 00:15:37.490
this is terrible.

00:15:37.490 --> 00:15:40.177
But I needed the money,
so I took this temp job

00:15:40.177 --> 00:15:42.510
at the Stanford Business
School, and it just so happened

00:15:42.510 --> 00:15:44.301
that I had landed, not
just in the business

00:15:44.301 --> 00:15:47.960
school, god forbid, but in the
Center for Social Innovation.

00:15:47.960 --> 00:15:49.530
This amazing place
where every day,

00:15:49.530 --> 00:15:51.071
people are coming
through those doors

00:15:51.071 --> 00:15:53.282
and thinking about how
to use business skills

00:15:53.282 --> 00:15:55.240
and business thinking to
solve social problems.

00:15:55.240 --> 00:15:58.310
So I realized very quickly
I was in a good place,

00:15:58.310 --> 00:16:01.120
I had kind of found my
people, and I learned so much

00:16:01.120 --> 00:16:03.330
over the next few years.

00:16:03.330 --> 00:16:05.460
I sat in on classes
and crashed lectures,

00:16:05.460 --> 00:16:07.600
I even, I kid you not,
went to office hours

00:16:07.600 --> 00:16:10.620
sometimes and told professors
I was not a student.

00:16:10.620 --> 00:16:13.810
I would be later and I would
pay a pretty penny for that.

00:16:13.810 --> 00:16:15.270
At the time, I was
just a staffer,

00:16:15.270 --> 00:16:17.770
but I would go and say look,
if you have no one else to talk

00:16:17.770 --> 00:16:20.325
to, can you, like, help me
understand the difference

00:16:20.325 --> 00:16:21.450
between profit and revenue?

00:16:21.450 --> 00:16:23.700
Which I actually never
got a hang of until later,

00:16:23.700 --> 00:16:27.120
but I get now.

00:16:27.120 --> 00:16:29.360
But I tried to be a
sponge and absorbed,

00:16:29.360 --> 00:16:33.060
sort of for free, an MBA,
and learn all that I could.

00:16:33.060 --> 00:16:35.740
Anyway, three years in to this
job, which changed and evolved.

00:16:35.740 --> 00:16:38.690
I mean, I clearly liked
it and I stuck around.

00:16:38.690 --> 00:16:40.360
There's this guy
named Doctor Muhammad

00:16:40.360 --> 00:16:41.660
Yunus, who came to campus.

00:16:41.660 --> 00:16:44.155
And so I stayed late after
work, it was in the fall

00:16:44.155 --> 00:16:46.940
of '03, three years before he
and his Grameen Bank would win

00:16:46.940 --> 00:16:49.580
the Nobel Peace Prize for
their work pioneering modern

00:16:49.580 --> 00:16:51.280
microfinance.

00:16:51.280 --> 00:16:53.461
And so I stayed after
work to hear him speak,

00:16:53.461 --> 00:16:55.960
sat in the back in case it was
lame and I could leave early.

00:16:55.960 --> 00:17:00.960
And in fact, it was my
little moment of epiphany.

00:17:00.960 --> 00:17:02.460
I learned about
microfinance, right?

00:17:02.460 --> 00:17:05.569
Financial services and products
for the entrepreneurial poor.

00:17:05.569 --> 00:17:08.440
Particularly microcredit,
loans, I learned about that,

00:17:08.440 --> 00:17:10.274
and it almost seemed magical.

00:17:10.274 --> 00:17:11.940
The idea that this
little bit of capital

00:17:11.940 --> 00:17:13.210
at the right time
in the right hands

00:17:13.210 --> 00:17:15.210
could change somebody's
trajectory, and help

00:17:15.210 --> 00:17:17.574
lift them and their
family out of property.

00:17:17.574 --> 00:17:20.690
It sounded amazing and I had
never heard about that before.

00:17:20.690 --> 00:17:21.696
So that was one thing.

00:17:21.696 --> 00:17:23.154
Secondly, he talked
about his story

00:17:23.154 --> 00:17:24.900
in a very accessible,
approachable way.

00:17:24.900 --> 00:17:28.630
So here I was, this
legit liberal arts major,

00:17:28.630 --> 00:17:30.440
but I had no idea what
to put on my resume.

00:17:30.440 --> 00:17:34.030
I didn't know what my skills
were, I couldn't code.

00:17:34.030 --> 00:17:36.020
I've since tried,
that's another story.

00:17:36.020 --> 00:17:38.420
It's pretty hard.

00:17:38.420 --> 00:17:41.150
I don't know if that's what
I'm meant to do in the world.

00:17:41.150 --> 00:17:42.974
But so I learned
about microfinance

00:17:42.974 --> 00:17:44.640
and I learned about
this amazing man who

00:17:44.640 --> 00:17:46.340
got his start by
basically, and I'm

00:17:46.340 --> 00:17:48.940
paraphrasing, leaving
the halls of academia

00:17:48.940 --> 00:17:51.640
where he had been a professor
at the University of Chittagong

00:17:51.640 --> 00:17:52.670
in Bangladesh.

00:17:52.670 --> 00:17:56.302
He one day goes and sits with a
group of women, basket weavers,

00:17:56.302 --> 00:17:58.010
and asks them directly
why they are poor.

00:17:58.010 --> 00:18:00.720
Asks them why they think they're
stuck in a cycle of poverty.

00:18:00.720 --> 00:18:02.750
And they tell their
stories to him.

00:18:02.750 --> 00:18:05.479
And he listens and he respond
in a very common sense way.

00:18:05.479 --> 00:18:07.770
Because they tell him that
every morning, they wake up,

00:18:07.770 --> 00:18:08.860
they have nothing,
they have to go

00:18:08.860 --> 00:18:10.735
to a local moneylender
who charges, you know,

00:18:10.735 --> 00:18:12.464
300 plus percent interest.

00:18:12.464 --> 00:18:14.130
They borrow a little
bit of money, often

00:18:14.130 --> 00:18:15.707
just a few dollars,
buy materials

00:18:15.707 --> 00:18:17.290
that they need to
weave their baskets,

00:18:17.290 --> 00:18:19.250
make a beautiful product,
sell it at a profit,

00:18:19.250 --> 00:18:23.480
but they owe everything back, if
not more, to the moneylenders.

00:18:23.480 --> 00:18:25.535
It's a very easy to
understand cycle of poverty

00:18:25.535 --> 00:18:27.000
that they were trapped in.

00:18:27.000 --> 00:18:29.450
At least when I heard
that from his story.

00:18:29.450 --> 00:18:31.420
And as it goes, he
reaches into his pocket,

00:18:31.420 --> 00:18:34.200
lends a little over $20 to
that village full of women,

00:18:34.200 --> 00:18:36.150
and indeed, they're
able to repay.

00:18:36.150 --> 00:18:38.710
Not with 300% interest,
and slowly change

00:18:38.710 --> 00:18:40.610
their lives for the better.

00:18:40.610 --> 00:18:43.080
That's what he did in
response to their stories.

00:18:43.080 --> 00:18:46.400
It seemed so common sense
and it seemed like something

00:18:46.400 --> 00:18:48.560
maybe even a philosophy
major could do.

00:18:48.560 --> 00:18:50.760
Go, sit, be a really
good listener,

00:18:50.760 --> 00:18:53.100
and maybe, maybe, maybe
hear something new,

00:18:53.100 --> 00:18:55.570
and respond in a common
sense way to help somebody.

00:18:55.570 --> 00:18:56.780
So one, microfinance.

00:18:56.780 --> 00:19:00.650
Two, maybe I could go listen to
people and do something good.

00:19:00.650 --> 00:19:03.500
And three, he talked
about the poor in a way

00:19:03.500 --> 00:19:06.110
that I hadn't heard, at
least in recent memory.

00:19:06.110 --> 00:19:08.250
He talked about people
who are smart, and strong,

00:19:08.250 --> 00:19:11.130
and hardworking, and very
intelligent, even if they might

00:19:11.130 --> 00:19:13.670
be unschooled, and
who just needed access

00:19:13.670 --> 00:19:16.220
to this little
thing, a small loan,

00:19:16.220 --> 00:19:18.530
to be able to do great things.

00:19:18.530 --> 00:19:20.890
It totally changed my paradigm.

00:19:20.890 --> 00:19:23.110
I mean, having spent a few
years in Silicon Valley

00:19:23.110 --> 00:19:25.000
by that point, I
mean, I figured out

00:19:25.000 --> 00:19:27.240
that an entrepreneur was a
pretty great thing to be.

00:19:27.240 --> 00:19:30.025
So suddenly, to tell me that
the poor could be entrepreneurs

00:19:30.025 --> 00:19:31.530
flipped everything on it's head.

00:19:31.530 --> 00:19:33.062
And I was so inspired,
in fact, this

00:19:33.062 --> 00:19:35.020
is another place where
I tell college students,

00:19:35.020 --> 00:19:36.853
like, don't do this or
don't blame it on me.

00:19:36.853 --> 00:19:39.470
But I quit my job at Stanford
and I moved to East Africa,

00:19:39.470 --> 00:19:42.570
and begged my way into a
basically unpaid internship,

00:19:42.570 --> 00:19:45.320
as I described, with
Village Enterprise.

00:19:45.320 --> 00:19:47.570
And they allowed me to have
this amazing opportunity

00:19:47.570 --> 00:19:50.040
for three months
to go, by myself,

00:19:50.040 --> 00:19:52.540
trump around Uganda,
and Kenya, and Tanzania

00:19:52.540 --> 00:19:56.080
and interview entrepreneurs and
ask them about their stories.

00:19:56.080 --> 00:19:58.970
And ask them how this $100
had changed their lives.

00:19:58.970 --> 00:20:01.840
So that's what it did,
And it was the best.

00:20:01.840 --> 00:20:04.670
It was so fun.

00:20:04.670 --> 00:20:06.750
Not only did I learn
a lot about business,

00:20:06.750 --> 00:20:09.100
I did finally, thanks to
goat herders, et cetera,

00:20:09.100 --> 00:20:11.350
learn about the difference
between profit and revenue.

00:20:11.350 --> 00:20:13.490
That's a lot of why I wrote the
book, because I feel like they

00:20:13.490 --> 00:20:14.609
really taught me business.

00:20:14.609 --> 00:20:15.650
Business school did, too.

00:20:15.650 --> 00:20:17.850
I mean, Standford
GSB is a great place.

00:20:17.850 --> 00:20:19.400
I recommend it, et cetera.

00:20:19.400 --> 00:20:23.780
But in all seriousness,
I mean, I so frequently

00:20:23.780 --> 00:20:26.620
thought back to my
conversations with entrepreneurs

00:20:26.620 --> 00:20:29.570
when I would learn a big,
fancy theory in class

00:20:29.570 --> 00:20:30.720
and say, oh, right.

00:20:30.720 --> 00:20:33.042
That was that thing that
fishmonger did, or oh,

00:20:33.042 --> 00:20:33.750
yeah, yeah, yeah.

00:20:33.750 --> 00:20:37.030
I remember, this is the way
the farmer did whatever.

00:20:37.030 --> 00:20:38.760
Those are my real life examples.

00:20:38.760 --> 00:20:40.970
Those were businesses
that I could understand.

00:20:40.970 --> 00:20:42.770
That are started with $100.

00:20:42.770 --> 00:20:44.840
It was a really nice
place to start for me.

00:20:44.840 --> 00:20:46.790
Anyway, so not only did
I learn a little bit

00:20:46.790 --> 00:20:49.630
about entrepreneurship
and business,

00:20:49.630 --> 00:20:52.760
but I had this new experience
that really changed

00:20:52.760 --> 00:20:55.060
the way I felt and
the way I thought

00:20:55.060 --> 00:20:57.940
and it opened my heart up
to different possibilities.

00:20:57.940 --> 00:21:01.426
I heard a new narrative
about poverty and potential.

00:21:01.426 --> 00:21:02.800
And I met people
who were smiling

00:21:02.800 --> 00:21:05.022
and actually happy with
their lives and the work

00:21:05.022 --> 00:21:06.980
that they were doing,
even though it was tough.

00:21:06.980 --> 00:21:09.080
I met people who already
had made great progress.

00:21:09.080 --> 00:21:10.829
Maybe had started with
a needle and thread

00:21:10.829 --> 00:21:13.420
under the shade of a tree,
and now had capital equipment

00:21:13.420 --> 00:21:14.800
and an office.

00:21:14.800 --> 00:21:16.220
I met people who
just, I happened

00:21:16.220 --> 00:21:18.540
to encounter in a scene of
abundance versus carefully

00:21:18.540 --> 00:21:21.410
crafted picture on a, you
know, marketing brochure

00:21:21.410 --> 00:21:23.484
for a nonprofit, of scarcity.

00:21:23.484 --> 00:21:24.650
And that changed how I fell.

00:21:24.650 --> 00:21:26.870
I met people who had full hands
with something to offer me,

00:21:26.870 --> 00:21:28.500
not empty ones
asking for a handout,

00:21:28.500 --> 00:21:32.240
as I had sort of maybe expected,
given all I'd heard before.

00:21:32.240 --> 00:21:34.340
It changed how I felt.
It change how I thought.

00:21:34.340 --> 00:21:36.912
And along with my
co-founder Matt,

00:21:36.912 --> 00:21:39.495
he was back in San Francisco and
I would call him and tell him

00:21:39.495 --> 00:21:41.203
all about the awesome
goatherder that I'd

00:21:41.203 --> 00:21:43.140
met, or the seamstress,
or whoever it was.

00:21:43.140 --> 00:21:44.410
And we thought two things.

00:21:44.410 --> 00:21:47.200
One, wouldn't it be fun
to tell this new story

00:21:47.200 --> 00:21:49.720
about these individuals
living in sub-Saharan Africa

00:21:49.720 --> 00:21:51.140
that I hadn't heard
before, and we

00:21:51.140 --> 00:21:53.348
didn't think a lot of other
people had heard, either.

00:21:53.348 --> 00:21:55.020
Stories of entrepreneurship.

00:21:55.020 --> 00:21:57.389
And two, instead of
just holding out the jar

00:21:57.389 --> 00:21:58.930
and having people
throw change in it,

00:21:58.930 --> 00:22:01.230
wouldn't it be great to engage
individuals in a new way

00:22:01.230 --> 00:22:03.080
and allow them to
respond differently, too.

00:22:03.080 --> 00:22:05.580
Maybe with a lone,
since, for the record,

00:22:05.580 --> 00:22:07.580
nobody had asked me for
a donation or a handout.

00:22:07.580 --> 00:22:08.500
Nobody.

00:22:08.500 --> 00:22:09.790
People had asked for loans.

00:22:09.790 --> 00:22:11.860
They wanted to build
something on their own,

00:22:11.860 --> 00:22:14.710
repay, and have
ownership and autonomy.

00:22:14.710 --> 00:22:17.110
So with those two
what-if questions.

00:22:17.110 --> 00:22:21.862
In the spring of '05, we put
seven entrepreneur's pictures,

00:22:21.862 --> 00:22:22.570
much like Sophia.

00:22:22.570 --> 00:22:26.540
Although she came later, but
here's Sophia there and here.

00:22:26.540 --> 00:22:28.320
We put seven
entrepreneurs from Uganda

00:22:28.320 --> 00:22:32.650
on to this little, basic,
scrappy website. thekiva.org.

00:22:32.650 --> 00:22:34.925
They needed about a total
of $3,000 in loan needs.

00:22:34.925 --> 00:22:36.800
We still don't know for
sure if it was legal.

00:22:36.800 --> 00:22:39.075
We had cold called the SCC and
hadn't gotten totally clear

00:22:39.075 --> 00:22:40.020
answers at that time.

00:22:40.020 --> 00:22:42.500
But we thought, surely
they won't come to our door

00:22:42.500 --> 00:22:45.140
and arrest us, we'll just try.

00:22:45.140 --> 00:22:47.407
So we spammed friends
and family, said

00:22:47.407 --> 00:22:49.240
our seven friends in
Uganda need some money,

00:22:49.240 --> 00:22:50.082
do you want to help?

00:22:50.082 --> 00:22:51.290
Overnight, the money came in.

00:22:51.290 --> 00:22:53.579
Now, to be very
clear, this was like,

00:22:53.579 --> 00:22:55.870
cash from my grandma and a
check from my mom, and like,

00:22:55.870 --> 00:22:57.536
we didn't have online
processing at all.

00:22:57.536 --> 00:22:59.670
It was just pictures
and stories.

00:22:59.670 --> 00:23:01.290
We had our personal
bank account.

00:23:01.290 --> 00:23:03.990
Wired it to another friend in
Uganda's personal bank account,

00:23:03.990 --> 00:23:06.690
and it was not an
illustrious, fancy beginning.

00:23:06.690 --> 00:23:08.110
It was very, very scrappy.

00:23:08.110 --> 00:23:10.590
But it was enough
to start, so we did.

00:23:10.590 --> 00:23:13.737
Over the next six months, by the
fall of '05, where I had just

00:23:13.737 --> 00:23:15.320
started business
school and was, like,

00:23:15.320 --> 00:23:18.840
drowning in accounting and
trying to pass my classes.

00:23:18.840 --> 00:23:21.370
The entrepreneurs were paid
and we said, look, we did it,

00:23:21.370 --> 00:23:21.870
we're real.

00:23:21.870 --> 00:23:23.245
Kiva is a real
thing, we're going

00:23:23.245 --> 00:23:25.852
to take the word beta off of
the site, and launch for real.

00:23:25.852 --> 00:23:28.060
Which meant nothing, except
our friend writing, like,

00:23:28.060 --> 00:23:31.510
a press release that we put
on our own site and that's it.

00:23:31.510 --> 00:23:32.809
That was a launch.

00:23:32.809 --> 00:23:35.100
We called our friend in
Uganda, put another dozen or so

00:23:35.100 --> 00:23:37.320
businesses on the
website, and just

00:23:37.320 --> 00:23:38.920
spammed our friends
and family again.

00:23:38.920 --> 00:23:41.390
And we told them they
could spread the word, too.

00:23:41.390 --> 00:23:44.585
So the first few weeks,
things were moving along,

00:23:44.585 --> 00:23:46.140
you know, rather quickly for us.

00:23:46.140 --> 00:23:49.210
I mean the loans got filled
and time was passing.

00:23:49.210 --> 00:23:52.190
But then, in November, a month
after we had taken that beta

00:23:52.190 --> 00:23:54.719
off of the site,
300 blogs suddenly

00:23:54.719 --> 00:23:57.260
wrote about Kiva, including two
of the three most widely read

00:23:57.260 --> 00:23:57.890
at the time.

00:23:57.890 --> 00:24:00.131
Daily Kos and Boing
Boing wrote about it.

00:24:00.131 --> 00:24:02.130
And suddenly, the site
was slammed with traffic,

00:24:02.130 --> 00:24:04.570
and it just kicked off this
crazy gear were somehow,

00:24:04.570 --> 00:24:07.610
in that first year, October '05
to '06, we facilitated about

00:24:07.610 --> 00:24:08.750
$500,000 in loans.

00:24:08.750 --> 00:24:11.110
The next year, the total
went up to $15 million,

00:24:11.110 --> 00:24:13.359
the next year $40 million,
the next year $100 million.

00:24:13.359 --> 00:24:15.220
Today, Kiva is about
to cross $750 million

00:24:15.220 --> 00:24:17.730
in loans in these little
$25 bits for people

00:24:17.730 --> 00:24:18.670
all over the planet.

00:24:18.670 --> 00:24:20.960
So it's been a crazy
thing to get to watch.

00:24:20.960 --> 00:24:23.510
And it's not just
loans in East Africa

00:24:23.510 --> 00:24:25.820
and it's not just
individuals, although, here's

00:24:25.820 --> 00:24:29.550
an example there, it's also
people in my own hometown.

00:24:29.550 --> 00:24:31.000
Any Pittsburghers in here?

00:24:31.000 --> 00:24:32.160
Just got to check.

00:24:32.160 --> 00:24:33.370
Go Steelers, right?

00:24:35.592 --> 00:24:37.050
So Kiva works
throughout the world.

00:24:37.050 --> 00:24:39.660
I'm happy to go more into
detail on Kiva if you'd like.

00:24:39.660 --> 00:24:42.260
Loans are not always just used
for business activities, too.

00:24:42.260 --> 00:24:43.360
They're used for other things.

00:24:43.360 --> 00:24:45.776
Sometimes housing, sometimes
it's their consumption loans,

00:24:45.776 --> 00:24:49.330
but investing, or lending money
to entrepreneurs on the site

00:24:49.330 --> 00:24:51.934
is still what the core
of Kiva is all about,

00:24:51.934 --> 00:24:53.600
and it's been really
a wonderful and fun

00:24:53.600 --> 00:24:55.014
experience to watch it grow.

00:24:55.014 --> 00:24:56.430
So that's just one
thing that I've

00:24:56.430 --> 00:24:58.450
had the honor of
being involved with.

00:24:58.450 --> 00:25:02.334
I left Kiva, I started another
company a few years ago.

00:25:02.334 --> 00:25:04.750
I worked for a venture fund
called the Collaborative Fund.

00:25:04.750 --> 00:25:08.520
Really fun that the fund
invests at the seed stage

00:25:08.520 --> 00:25:10.350
in sharing economy
type companies.

00:25:10.350 --> 00:25:13.060
Could talk about that more
if you'd like, but here's

00:25:13.060 --> 00:25:15.020
what I kind of want to end on.

00:25:15.020 --> 00:25:17.797
So my definition of poverty
has kind of changed over time.

00:25:17.797 --> 00:25:19.630
I still very much believe
that at its heart,

00:25:19.630 --> 00:25:23.010
it's really about lack of access
to basic things, basic needs.

00:25:23.010 --> 00:25:28.710
Food, clothing, shelter, basic
health care, information.

00:25:28.710 --> 00:25:30.440
I think it's about
a lack of access

00:25:30.440 --> 00:25:35.185
to opportunity and lack of basic
freedoms, lack of capability.

00:25:35.185 --> 00:25:36.820
But here's the thing.

00:25:36.820 --> 00:25:38.790
Day to day in my
life now, I encounter

00:25:38.790 --> 00:25:41.510
a lot of other kinds of needs,
too, that are often invisible.

00:25:41.510 --> 00:25:45.070
And often, the things
that are the greatest

00:25:45.070 --> 00:25:46.960
need in communities
like this where

00:25:46.960 --> 00:25:49.490
we're all quite privileged
and quite blessed with all

00:25:49.490 --> 00:25:50.640
that we have.

00:25:50.640 --> 00:25:54.650
And I find that just as sad.

00:25:54.650 --> 00:25:57.020
I meet people all the time
who might be very wealthy

00:25:57.020 --> 00:26:01.630
materially, but are poor
creatively, or emotionally,

00:26:01.630 --> 00:26:03.432
or spiritually, and
they feel stuck,

00:26:03.432 --> 00:26:05.890
even though they have everything
they need to move forward.

00:26:05.890 --> 00:26:07.800
They feel trapped even
though they're free

00:26:07.800 --> 00:26:10.480
and I think that's tragic
in its own way I think

00:26:10.480 --> 00:26:13.790
the main problem is that
they, like many others all

00:26:13.790 --> 00:26:16.320
around the world, have
forgotten, just temporarily

00:26:16.320 --> 00:26:19.120
hopefully, that they can
imagine and then pursue

00:26:19.120 --> 00:26:21.190
a different future for
themselves, whatever

00:26:21.190 --> 00:26:23.400
that looks like.

00:26:23.400 --> 00:26:25.330
So I would just like
to remind us today,

00:26:25.330 --> 00:26:28.354
please don't believe
the wrong stories.

00:26:28.354 --> 00:26:29.770
The ones that are
incomplete, just

00:26:29.770 --> 00:26:31.202
telling one side of things.

00:26:31.202 --> 00:26:33.785
Don't believe the wrong stories,
especially about other people

00:26:33.785 --> 00:26:35.840
and about what's possible
in the world for them.

00:26:35.840 --> 00:26:37.400
And don't believe the
stories that tell you,

00:26:37.400 --> 00:26:39.310
you can only respond
in one particular way.

00:26:39.310 --> 00:26:41.540
That you're only needed
for this one thing

00:26:41.540 --> 00:26:44.790
you might have, whether
it's financial contributions

00:26:44.790 --> 00:26:47.452
or something else.

00:26:47.452 --> 00:26:49.160
I want you to practice,
I hope we can all

00:26:49.160 --> 00:26:51.360
practice imagining a
new and a better future.

00:26:51.360 --> 00:26:54.830
One that reminds us that
more is always possible.

00:26:57.390 --> 00:26:58.910
I ask this for very
selfish reasons.

00:26:58.910 --> 00:27:01.010
I want my kids, I know
it's totally cheating

00:27:01.010 --> 00:27:02.010
to end on a kid picture.

00:27:02.010 --> 00:27:03.968
And one of them is here,
the other two are not,

00:27:03.968 --> 00:27:06.130
because that would have
been a little crazy.

00:27:06.130 --> 00:27:08.740
I wanted to stories that
my kids hear, and believe,

00:27:08.740 --> 00:27:12.390
and internalized to be ones that
convince them of the reality

00:27:12.390 --> 00:27:14.170
that opportunity is
everywhere, sometimes

00:27:14.170 --> 00:27:15.669
even in the ground
beneath our feet.

00:27:15.669 --> 00:27:18.560
And that human
potential is everywhere

00:27:18.560 --> 00:27:22.540
around the world, even,
and especially, inside

00:27:22.540 --> 00:27:23.220
each one of us.

00:27:23.220 --> 00:27:24.830
