00:29:23.109 --> 00:29:25.400
AUDIENCE: What advice would
you give for someone that's

00:29:25.400 --> 00:29:27.560
interested in social change?

00:29:27.560 --> 00:29:29.640
JESSICA JACKLEY:
That's a nice question.

00:29:29.640 --> 00:29:34.714
I would say, get
specific and personal

00:29:34.714 --> 00:29:35.880
about who you want to serve.

00:29:35.880 --> 00:29:38.810
That's, for me, I think the
best question to start with.

00:29:38.810 --> 00:29:41.280
There are lots of objectively
good things to the world.

00:29:41.280 --> 00:29:42.370
There's a lot of needs.

00:29:42.370 --> 00:29:45.850
You can, I think, go crazy
if you try to just make it

00:29:45.850 --> 00:29:49.020
about, where will I make the
most impact in a general way,

00:29:49.020 --> 00:29:49.520
right?

00:29:49.520 --> 00:29:51.490
Like where will my
dollar do us good?

00:29:51.490 --> 00:29:53.920
Definitely research that
stuff and figure it out,

00:29:53.920 --> 00:29:55.190
but go with your heart.

00:29:55.190 --> 00:29:56.731
Go with what you're
passionate about,

00:29:56.731 --> 00:30:00.320
and then get close to the
people you want to serve, ASAP.

00:30:00.320 --> 00:30:00.940
Right away.

00:30:00.940 --> 00:30:03.120
Early in your career if
you can, but at any time,

00:30:03.120 --> 00:30:05.320
just make a point to get
out of your comfort zone

00:30:05.320 --> 00:30:07.486
and go spend time with the
people you want to serve.

00:30:07.486 --> 00:30:13.180
One of my favorite books is Paul
Polak's book, "Out of Poverty,"

00:30:13.180 --> 00:30:16.140
and he basically says--
I'll just paraphrase him--

00:30:16.140 --> 00:30:18.250
he basically says, like
in the first few chapters.

00:30:18.250 --> 00:30:21.250
Look, don't even try to go help
people far away if you haven't

00:30:21.250 --> 00:30:22.940
spent major time with them,
because you'll probably

00:30:22.940 --> 00:30:23.390
screw it up.

00:30:23.390 --> 00:30:24.800
He's not that harsh
about it, but it's

00:30:24.800 --> 00:30:26.030
kind of what he's anything.

00:30:26.030 --> 00:30:28.500
And there are lots of,
probably as you know,

00:30:28.500 --> 00:30:30.600
stories of people
with great big heart

00:30:30.600 --> 00:30:33.940
and great intentions that just
missed the mark because they

00:30:33.940 --> 00:30:36.144
think they have a great
idea of how to help,

00:30:36.144 --> 00:30:38.810
but it actually doesn't map with
what people need on the ground.

00:30:38.810 --> 00:30:41.570
So get there, get
close, get personal,

00:30:41.570 --> 00:30:43.057
and be a really good listener.

00:30:43.057 --> 00:30:45.640
AUDIENCE: You talked about how
Kiva kind of was such a success

00:30:45.640 --> 00:30:47.270
and grew, and grew,
and grew, but I'm

00:30:47.270 --> 00:30:49.590
sure you faced some
challenges along the way.

00:30:49.590 --> 00:30:52.470
And I'd love to here kind of
what some of those challenges

00:30:52.470 --> 00:30:52.970
were.

00:30:52.970 --> 00:30:54.761
JESSICA JACKLEY: How
much time do you have?

00:30:54.761 --> 00:30:55.750
Yes.

00:30:55.750 --> 00:30:58.130
AUDIENCE: But also, what
motivated you to keep going,

00:30:58.130 --> 00:31:01.546
and, you know, how you were able
to overcome those challenges.

00:31:01.546 --> 00:31:03.170
JESSICA JACKLEY:
Really great question.

00:31:05.730 --> 00:31:07.170
So I'll start with
the easy stuff.

00:31:07.170 --> 00:31:09.380
The easy challenges
were more up here.

00:31:09.380 --> 00:31:12.720
Like people-- In the
very, very beginning, when

00:31:12.720 --> 00:31:15.560
we had this idea, hey, wouldn't
it be fun to loan money

00:31:15.560 --> 00:31:19.150
to our friends in
Uganda and beyond?

00:31:19.150 --> 00:31:22.720
Traditional for-profit types and
socially responsible investment

00:31:22.720 --> 00:31:23.800
folks, I mean experts.

00:31:23.800 --> 00:31:25.630
People who had
decades of experience,

00:31:25.630 --> 00:31:28.030
push back and would say
things, like, well, why would

00:31:28.030 --> 00:31:30.400
you think somebody would want
to do this weird 0% loan.

00:31:30.400 --> 00:31:31.680
There's no financial return.

00:31:31.680 --> 00:31:34.230
And on the other side,
nonprofit folks were like,

00:31:34.230 --> 00:31:35.770
it's not a
tax-deductible donation.

00:31:35.770 --> 00:31:36.321
That's silly.

00:31:36.321 --> 00:31:38.820
But we thought maybe there was
going to be a market for that

00:31:38.820 --> 00:31:40.590
anyway, and there is.

00:31:40.590 --> 00:31:42.124
But that was one
thing we got back,

00:31:42.124 --> 00:31:43.540
so that was one
piece of criticism

00:31:43.540 --> 00:31:46.110
that, it's easy
to rattle off now,

00:31:46.110 --> 00:31:50.114
but it was a little
bit crazy making.

00:31:50.114 --> 00:31:52.280
I think a lot happened up
here in the very beginning

00:31:52.280 --> 00:31:55.141
of ventures where a
lot of entrepreneurship

00:31:55.141 --> 00:31:56.140
feels like make believe.

00:31:56.140 --> 00:31:58.110
You have this vision for
the future and your kind

00:31:58.110 --> 00:31:59.130
of imagining what
the world would

00:31:59.130 --> 00:32:00.220
be like you can get there.

00:32:00.220 --> 00:32:02.250
And you're trying to
make make believe.

00:32:02.250 --> 00:32:04.810
You're trying to make the
thing that's in your head real.

00:32:04.810 --> 00:32:07.185
And when other people tell
you it's silly, or impossible,

00:32:07.185 --> 00:32:08.780
or won't work, it
can rattle you.

00:32:08.780 --> 00:32:12.830
So that's like the least of
the issues, of the challenges,

00:32:12.830 --> 00:32:14.360
but it was something
to overcome.

00:32:14.360 --> 00:32:17.440
There were also other challenges
at the beginning around, which

00:32:17.440 --> 00:32:19.940
we can all sort of giggle that
now, that around, you know,

00:32:19.940 --> 00:32:21.730
will technology really
spread that fast?

00:32:21.730 --> 00:32:24.900
Will you really be able to get
a picture of people in Africa?

00:32:24.900 --> 00:32:26.350
It was kind of funny.

00:32:26.350 --> 00:32:32.010
And that was easier to fight and
to just prove to be incorrect.

00:32:32.010 --> 00:32:34.060
The harder stuff was
the emotional stuff.

00:32:34.060 --> 00:32:38.660
So that picture of me with
the turkey, 10 years ago.

00:32:38.660 --> 00:32:41.920
During that time, I lived with a
family, just for a short while,

00:32:41.920 --> 00:32:46.900
but became really close friends
with the family in Uganda,

00:32:46.900 --> 00:32:49.620
and this guy Moses was
one of our-- virtually

00:32:49.620 --> 00:32:53.050
a co-founder with Matt
and me-- and became

00:32:53.050 --> 00:32:53.930
a really good friend.

00:32:53.930 --> 00:32:58.050
And over the first year, because
we had this onslaught of demand

00:32:58.050 --> 00:33:01.150
from would-be lenders,
I'm not to say

00:33:01.150 --> 00:33:03.360
we created a monster because
he's a wonderful person,

00:33:03.360 --> 00:33:05.120
we definitely made
it difficult for him

00:33:05.120 --> 00:33:07.540
and put a lot of
temptation in front of him.

00:33:07.540 --> 00:33:09.250
He was a pastor in
this small village

00:33:09.250 --> 00:33:11.708
and it had only ever seen a
few thousand dollars at any one

00:33:11.708 --> 00:33:12.484
time, if that.

00:33:12.484 --> 00:33:14.900
And suddenly, we were, like,
pushing hundreds of thousands

00:33:14.900 --> 00:33:17.110
at him to distribute.

00:33:17.110 --> 00:33:18.360
That's a lot of entrepreneurs.

00:33:18.360 --> 00:33:20.370
And so there was
a case of fraud,

00:33:20.370 --> 00:33:22.460
and it was just kind
of heartbreaking to see

00:33:22.460 --> 00:33:24.760
our friend make bad choices.

00:33:24.760 --> 00:33:29.550
But we were so green, and
so, I'll use the word naive,

00:33:29.550 --> 00:33:32.740
and had not build in the right
systems for accountability,

00:33:32.740 --> 00:33:34.490
and transparency, and
that sort of thing.

00:33:34.490 --> 00:33:37.285
So the good part
of that was that we

00:33:37.285 --> 00:33:39.660
were able to respond with,
OK, what do we need to change?

00:33:39.660 --> 00:33:40.785
What do we need to improve?

00:33:40.785 --> 00:33:42.830
And over time, a lot
of great improvements,

00:33:42.830 --> 00:33:44.710
I think, to the
product and to the site

00:33:44.710 --> 00:33:46.350
in general have
been because we've

00:33:46.350 --> 00:33:50.640
been pushed to get better, and
to refine, and to iterating.

00:33:50.640 --> 00:33:53.560
Sometimes, because something not
great happens, but other times,

00:33:53.560 --> 00:33:56.720
just because that's what you do.

00:33:56.720 --> 00:33:59.055
So I think the really important
part of your questions

00:33:59.055 --> 00:34:01.530
is, how do you get
through those times?

00:34:01.530 --> 00:34:04.160
One, I don't think it's
ever really smart, at least

00:34:04.160 --> 00:34:06.384
not for me, I'll speak
for me personally.

00:34:06.384 --> 00:34:08.050
I don't think it's
great to go in alone.

00:34:08.050 --> 00:34:10.133
I always had people around
me, whether it was just

00:34:10.133 --> 00:34:12.000
friends or family,
or my co-founder,

00:34:12.000 --> 00:34:15.177
or the early team that
believed in the vision, too.

00:34:15.177 --> 00:34:16.010
And said no, no, no.

00:34:16.010 --> 00:34:18.300
Remember, it's real, this
is where we're going,

00:34:18.300 --> 00:34:19.310
we got to keep at it.

00:34:19.310 --> 00:34:21.050
It's just the encouragement
of people really helped.

00:34:21.050 --> 00:34:23.510
But also, I think at some
point, you just need to, like,

00:34:23.510 --> 00:34:27.340
make a choice to see
the good in people

00:34:27.340 --> 00:34:29.886
and believe that it's still
there and believe that.

00:34:29.886 --> 00:34:30.469
It's so funny.

00:34:30.469 --> 00:34:33.739
I did-- it was really fun,
kind of a bucket list thing

00:34:33.739 --> 00:34:36.850
for me-- it did a forum this
morning with Michael Krasny,

00:34:36.850 --> 00:34:37.642
and it was an hour.

00:34:37.642 --> 00:34:39.016
And in between
all the breaks, he

00:34:39.016 --> 00:34:41.179
was like pushing me on
the goodness of people

00:34:41.179 --> 00:34:43.100
and he thought it was
very Pollyanna about it,

00:34:43.100 --> 00:34:45.460
and we had a nice
healthy debate.

00:34:45.460 --> 00:34:48.830
I really think you look
at a lot of the sad stuff,

00:34:48.830 --> 00:34:50.570
the bad things
that are happening

00:34:50.570 --> 00:34:52.039
in the world and
the bad choices.

00:34:52.039 --> 00:34:53.080
I'm such a parent, right?

00:34:53.080 --> 00:34:55.827
I'm like, you made a bad choice.

00:34:55.827 --> 00:34:57.759
Sorry, I'm suddenly,
like, I notice

00:34:57.759 --> 00:34:59.300
I'm using more and
more mom language.

00:34:59.300 --> 00:35:01.430
Oh my lord.

00:35:01.430 --> 00:35:02.200
Yeah.

00:35:02.200 --> 00:35:05.670
So when you see that, I really
see people who are hurting,

00:35:05.670 --> 00:35:08.460
who haven't been given even a
fraction of the opportunities

00:35:08.460 --> 00:35:09.920
that I've been given.

00:35:09.920 --> 00:35:13.840
And I think their
reactions to the world

00:35:13.840 --> 00:35:16.340
aren't always forgivable,
but are understandable.

00:35:16.340 --> 00:35:17.960
I can see where they come from.

00:35:17.960 --> 00:35:20.960
So I think you need to choose
to believe that we all start out

00:35:20.960 --> 00:35:23.675
with great intentions and
the same common desires.

00:35:23.675 --> 00:35:26.714
And the more and more we can
provide opportunity to people,

00:35:26.714 --> 00:35:27.630
the better things get.

00:35:27.630 --> 00:35:30.660
And then the more
the good in all of us

00:35:30.660 --> 00:35:31.935
can come out more easily.

00:35:31.935 --> 00:35:33.830
I think you just have
to make a choice.

00:35:33.830 --> 00:35:35.538
AUDIENCE: So as you've
traveled the world

00:35:35.538 --> 00:35:37.740
and met a diverse
group of people,

00:35:37.740 --> 00:35:39.740
what is their perspective on us?

00:35:39.740 --> 00:35:40.350
On America?

00:35:40.350 --> 00:35:41.800
On people from America?

00:35:41.800 --> 00:35:43.230
How does their world see us?

00:35:43.230 --> 00:35:45.180
And a follow up
to that would be,

00:35:45.180 --> 00:35:48.030
regardless of color,
or country, village,

00:35:48.030 --> 00:35:49.540
what is the common
theme that you've

00:35:49.540 --> 00:35:51.582
heard from all of these folks.

00:35:51.582 --> 00:35:53.082
That one thing that
you would break?

00:35:53.082 --> 00:35:56.690
JESSICA JACKLEY:
Yeah, so I guess

00:35:56.690 --> 00:35:59.370
it's very hard to
measure a generalization.

00:35:59.370 --> 00:36:02.550
And it's probably
self-selected, but the people

00:36:02.550 --> 00:36:06.800
that I have encountered have
been people that, in some way,

00:36:06.800 --> 00:36:10.716
have been connected to, I
think, good organizations

00:36:10.716 --> 00:36:11.840
that I have been a part of.

00:36:11.840 --> 00:36:14.256
So I've kind of encountered a
lot of really friendly, nice

00:36:14.256 --> 00:36:16.110
people who are very
happy, and thankful,

00:36:16.110 --> 00:36:20.860
and excited to talk about
Americans and the US.

00:36:20.860 --> 00:36:23.100
I know that there is other
sentiment out there, too,

00:36:23.100 --> 00:36:25.970
but I've encountered
a lot of good will.

00:36:25.970 --> 00:36:30.104
What's, I think, also positive
and notable with the Kiva

00:36:30.104 --> 00:36:31.270
experience, in particularly.

00:36:31.270 --> 00:36:34.180
Even though a lot of lenders are
in North America, not all are.

00:36:34.180 --> 00:36:37.300
And so to be able
to talk to borrowers

00:36:37.300 --> 00:36:39.822
about this global
community of supporters,

00:36:39.822 --> 00:36:41.280
I mean, almost all
over the planet.

00:36:41.280 --> 00:36:42.946
When you look at the
number of countries

00:36:42.946 --> 00:36:45.120
where borrowers and
lenders are, it's all over.

00:36:45.120 --> 00:36:48.300
So to be able to say there is
this global community of people

00:36:48.300 --> 00:36:50.960
who have read your story, who
care, at least enough to chip

00:36:50.960 --> 00:36:53.815
in $25, if not more,
who are cheering you on

00:36:53.815 --> 00:36:54.940
and think you're important.

00:36:54.940 --> 00:36:57.357
That's a really wonderful
message to be able to deliver.

00:36:57.357 --> 00:36:59.190
So I think all else
being equal, and maybe I

00:36:59.190 --> 00:37:01.310
am being a little bit
too utopian about it,

00:37:01.310 --> 00:37:05.010
but all else being
equal, to be able to have

00:37:05.010 --> 00:37:07.810
a loan, versus a loan with
all these people behind it.

00:37:07.810 --> 00:37:09.990
I think that's a
really beautiful option

00:37:09.990 --> 00:37:12.140
and I think that's well
received in most places.

00:37:12.140 --> 00:37:14.120
That's been my experience.

00:37:14.120 --> 00:37:16.780
What's the one sentiment
I've encountered

00:37:16.780 --> 00:37:19.730
in all these entrepreneurs?

00:37:19.730 --> 00:37:23.280
I have just been blown away
by the perseverance that

00:37:23.280 --> 00:37:26.890
exists to make life just
a little bit better.

00:37:26.890 --> 00:37:28.640
Now sometimes it's
only relatively better.

00:37:28.640 --> 00:37:30.139
Sometimes it's in
this absolute way,

00:37:30.139 --> 00:37:32.922
but again and again, the drive
that I see in individuals

00:37:32.922 --> 00:37:34.380
to make life better
for themselves,

00:37:34.380 --> 00:37:39.070
and more often than
not, for their families,

00:37:39.070 --> 00:37:42.540
it's so palpable, and it's
so powerful, it blows me way.

00:37:42.540 --> 00:37:45.000
And part of what
I'm really hopeful

00:37:45.000 --> 00:37:47.390
comes across in the
book is that, hopefully,

00:37:47.390 --> 00:37:51.680
I honor those and celebrate
those kinds of stories.

00:37:51.680 --> 00:37:55.450
People make it work, even
when it seems like it can't.

00:37:55.450 --> 00:37:58.809
And I feel so lucky that
I've gotten to see that.

00:37:58.809 --> 00:38:00.850
AUDIENCE: I am really
interested, now that you've

00:38:00.850 --> 00:38:04.760
scaled, how you vet
all of the people who

00:38:04.760 --> 00:38:05.840
are asking for loans.

00:38:05.840 --> 00:38:08.324
And I've heard different
things about, in general,

00:38:08.324 --> 00:38:10.240
like, working with
partners in different ways.

00:38:10.240 --> 00:38:11.600
And I don't know that's
related or unrelated to this,

00:38:11.600 --> 00:38:13.730
but I'd love to understand,
kind of, that dynamic

00:38:13.730 --> 00:38:14.320
and how it all works.

00:38:14.320 --> 00:38:14.610
JESSICA JACKLEY: Sure.

00:38:14.610 --> 00:38:16.870
So it is no longer just
me running around Uganda

00:38:16.870 --> 00:38:18.040
with my camera, thank God.

00:38:18.040 --> 00:38:19.300
It would be super
fun, but it would not

00:38:19.300 --> 00:38:20.440
be scalable, as they say.

00:38:20.440 --> 00:38:26.504
So classic Kiva, there's
two ways Kiva works today.

00:38:26.504 --> 00:38:27.920
The way it's worked
traditionally,

00:38:27.920 --> 00:38:31.200
and still does for the majority
of loans, is this, as follows.

00:38:31.200 --> 00:38:33.640
So you have lenders
come to the website

00:38:33.640 --> 00:38:37.320
that Kiva runs and there
are field partners that

00:38:37.320 --> 00:38:38.609
actually are out there.

00:38:38.609 --> 00:38:39.650
These banks for the poor.

00:38:39.650 --> 00:38:40.820
Kind of the Grameen
Banks of the world,

00:38:40.820 --> 00:38:42.160
but there are many
other types as well,

00:38:42.160 --> 00:38:44.201
and a lot of kind of
nontraditional partners now,

00:38:44.201 --> 00:38:45.860
not just microfinance
institutions.

00:38:45.860 --> 00:38:49.094
Maybe NGOs that also happened
to get loans, in addition

00:38:49.094 --> 00:38:49.760
to other things.

00:38:49.760 --> 00:38:52.040
So you have lenders
that come to the site

00:38:52.040 --> 00:38:54.522
that Kiva perpetuates,
you have field partners,

00:38:54.522 --> 00:38:55.480
and you have borrowers.

00:38:55.480 --> 00:38:56.890
There's sort of four parts.

00:38:56.890 --> 00:38:59.320
Lenders chip in their $25,
it goes through the site,

00:38:59.320 --> 00:38:59.930
Kiva doesn't touch it.

00:38:59.930 --> 00:39:01.540
It goes through the
microfinance institution,

00:39:01.540 --> 00:39:02.180
they don't touch it.

00:39:02.180 --> 00:39:03.890
It goes into the
hands of the borrower.

00:39:03.890 --> 00:39:05.520
The borrower repays
with interest

00:39:05.520 --> 00:39:08.820
that's fair and appropriate
and set by those by those field

00:39:08.820 --> 00:39:10.340
partners, to make
it more general.

00:39:10.340 --> 00:39:13.209
Sometimes that could be 20%,
30%, but you have to remember,

00:39:13.209 --> 00:39:15.000
you have to compare it
to the right things,

00:39:15.000 --> 00:39:16.458
and you have to
understand what are

00:39:16.458 --> 00:39:18.090
the other alternatives, if any?

00:39:18.090 --> 00:39:21.160
And often, it helps,
I think, to understand

00:39:21.160 --> 00:39:24.680
the incredible amount of work
that is necessary, usually,

00:39:24.680 --> 00:39:26.610
to reach a borrower
in a very rural area.

00:39:26.610 --> 00:39:29.090
To get out there and do weeks
of training, if not months,

00:39:29.090 --> 00:39:30.060
to collect repayment.

00:39:30.060 --> 00:39:33.457
Sometimes every week after
the loan has been dispersed.

00:39:33.457 --> 00:39:35.040
So interest rates
kind of makes sense,

00:39:35.040 --> 00:39:38.002
and Kiva only works
with ones that,

00:39:38.002 --> 00:39:39.460
at least the
organization believes,

00:39:39.460 --> 00:39:40.920
are fair, and
appropriate, and OK.

00:39:40.920 --> 00:39:43.600
So anyway, loans are paid
with a little bit of interest,

00:39:43.600 --> 00:39:45.477
the interest is kept
by the field partner,

00:39:45.477 --> 00:39:47.810
the principal comes back
through Kiva and into the hands

00:39:47.810 --> 00:39:48.518
of the borrowers.

00:39:48.518 --> 00:39:50.941
Kiva never takes
any out of that.

00:39:50.941 --> 00:39:52.690
The only thing that
can happen, so there's

00:39:52.690 --> 00:39:55.180
a few things that can happen,
if this is interesting.

00:39:55.180 --> 00:39:55.960
So-- Oh, sorry.

00:39:55.960 --> 00:39:56.460
Lenders.

00:39:56.460 --> 00:39:58.926
I said borrowers, but
lenders, they're over here.

00:39:58.926 --> 00:40:01.550
Lenders take on default risk, as
well as currency exchange risk

00:40:01.550 --> 00:40:03.720
in some cases, so they might
not receive all the money back,

00:40:03.720 --> 00:40:05.261
or not at all, but
that's quite rare.

00:40:05.261 --> 00:40:07.820
Repayment rates are
almost 99% on average,

00:40:07.820 --> 00:40:10.160
so usually the money comes
back and everything's great.

00:40:10.160 --> 00:40:11.870
That's Kiva classic, OK?

00:40:11.870 --> 00:40:14.360
So the way to answer
your first question.

00:40:14.360 --> 00:40:16.820
I think you asked two, but I'm
going to make it two anyway.

00:40:16.820 --> 00:40:19.010
And the way that the
borrowers are vetted,

00:40:19.010 --> 00:40:21.730
it is all done on the ground
by these experts, these expert

00:40:21.730 --> 00:40:24.010
organizations that
know their stuff,

00:40:24.010 --> 00:40:25.810
they're in the
community, they've

00:40:25.810 --> 00:40:27.410
already existed
before Kiva usually.

00:40:30.250 --> 00:40:32.500
They have their own ways of
doing training and vetting

00:40:32.500 --> 00:40:33.620
and all that stuff.

00:40:33.620 --> 00:40:34.770
So that's how that happens.

00:40:34.770 --> 00:40:36.510
Now, there's also, over
the last few years,

00:40:36.510 --> 00:40:38.690
a new way that Kiva has been
doing things called Kiva's If.

00:40:38.690 --> 00:40:40.330
And for the sake of
time, I'll explain

00:40:40.330 --> 00:40:42.590
it super, super concisely.

00:40:42.590 --> 00:40:46.250
Instead of lender, Kiva,
field partner, borrower.

00:40:46.250 --> 00:40:49.860
It's lender, Kiva, trustee--
just an individual-- borrower.

00:40:49.860 --> 00:40:52.510
And it's much more direct and
it's kind of like Kiva-lite.

00:40:52.510 --> 00:40:55.530
And the trustee just vouches for
the reputation of the borrower.

00:40:55.530 --> 00:40:58.910
I think that's the way, at
least in the US, for sure,

00:40:58.910 --> 00:41:01.590
but I think in other places, the
way things are going to move.

00:41:01.590 --> 00:41:04.232
And it's lighter, it's more
mobile, it's exciting stuff.

00:41:04.232 --> 00:41:06.190
AUDIENCE: If you're,
depending on how close you

00:41:06.190 --> 00:41:08.210
are to the field partners,
like, how did they

00:41:08.210 --> 00:41:11.220
vet someone to know if they
are right for a loan or not?

00:41:11.220 --> 00:41:12.992
JESSICA JACKLEY: Great, OK.

00:41:12.992 --> 00:41:14.700
You can totally
interrupt me and be like,

00:41:14.700 --> 00:41:15.930
that's not what I asked.

00:41:15.930 --> 00:41:16.430
Reroute.

00:41:16.430 --> 00:41:17.410
AUDIENCE: Super
interesting, I promise.

00:41:17.410 --> 00:41:18.360
Thank you for saying all that.

00:41:18.360 --> 00:41:19.526
JESSICA JACKLEY: No problem.

00:41:19.526 --> 00:41:22.842
So field partners, they each
have their own set of criteria.

00:41:22.842 --> 00:41:24.300
So now, my answer
is not even going

00:41:24.300 --> 00:41:25.340
to be satisfying,
because it's going

00:41:25.340 --> 00:41:26.464
to be an it depends answer.

00:41:26.464 --> 00:41:28.320
But they all have their
own set of criteria.

00:41:28.320 --> 00:41:31.062
Some only serve
women, some require

00:41:31.062 --> 00:41:32.895
training before you can
even apply for loan.

00:41:32.895 --> 00:41:36.780
Some have quite long
application processes.

00:41:36.780 --> 00:41:39.790
It's all different,
but they, again, they

00:41:39.790 --> 00:41:42.322
kind of know their communities
and know how to do that.

00:41:42.322 --> 00:41:43.280
We can talk more after.

00:41:43.280 --> 00:41:43.990
Is that OK?

00:41:43.990 --> 00:41:44.350
I feel like that'll--

00:41:44.350 --> 00:41:44.710
AUDIENCE: Yea, thank you.

00:41:44.710 --> 00:41:46.733
JESSICA JACKLEY: --That's
my best I can do.

00:41:46.733 --> 00:41:47.500
OK.

00:41:47.500 --> 00:41:48.510
AUDIENCE: So I just
have a question

00:41:48.510 --> 00:41:50.750
about what sort of makes
a good story in your mind,

00:41:50.750 --> 00:41:52.583
and how you go about
making sure that you're

00:41:52.583 --> 00:41:53.651
creating the right story.

00:41:53.651 --> 00:41:55.400
I can already see
challenges around things

00:41:55.400 --> 00:41:57.110
like trying to make a
representative story

00:41:57.110 --> 00:41:58.526
versus a really
inspirational one,

00:41:58.526 --> 00:42:01.051
or whose perspective
from a storyteller

00:42:01.051 --> 00:42:02.050
is sort of being served.

00:42:02.050 --> 00:42:03.250
You or sort of the
actor involved.

00:42:03.250 --> 00:42:05.200
So I'm wondering how you
approach all those questions.

00:42:05.200 --> 00:42:06.470
JESSICA JACKLEY: Well,
so one of the things--

00:42:06.470 --> 00:42:08.178
I want to be super
clear, because I'm not

00:42:08.178 --> 00:42:10.200
their day to day's, full
time, everyday staff.

00:42:10.200 --> 00:42:12.010
I feel like a grandma, like,
I get to be really proud

00:42:12.010 --> 00:42:14.170
and show pictures, been I'm
doing hard work every day.

00:42:14.170 --> 00:42:16.586
So I don't want to speak for
exactly what's happening now,

00:42:16.586 --> 00:42:20.380
but I will say, at the
beginning, first early years,

00:42:20.380 --> 00:42:23.035
we were really excited not
to have it be too polished.

00:42:23.035 --> 00:42:24.910
To just have whatever
people wanted to put up

00:42:24.910 --> 00:42:26.760
there speaks for
itself, and have

00:42:26.760 --> 00:42:29.740
kind of the opposite of this
very carefully crafted, kind

00:42:29.740 --> 00:42:32.370
of manipulated story,
that we saw so much

00:42:32.370 --> 00:42:35.001
from other organizations that
probably kind of gamified it,

00:42:35.001 --> 00:42:35.500
right?

00:42:35.500 --> 00:42:37.749
Like they knew exactly what
keywords to put in to make

00:42:37.749 --> 00:42:40.310
it hit you in a particular way.

00:42:40.310 --> 00:42:42.960
So right now, what happens
is those field partners,

00:42:42.960 --> 00:42:45.664
see your other question
there was a great setup,

00:42:45.664 --> 00:42:47.330
so now you know what
a field partner is.

00:42:47.330 --> 00:42:49.538
They have loan officers or
other representatives that

00:42:49.538 --> 00:42:51.730
are out there with
borrowers, and while they

00:42:51.730 --> 00:42:53.210
are the ones that bring
the information back,

00:42:53.210 --> 00:42:54.500
it's not like the
borrowers are typing up

00:42:54.500 --> 00:42:56.985
their own stories at this
point, at least in Kiva classic.

00:43:00.546 --> 00:43:02.670
They might have basic
guidelines on, like, question

00:43:02.670 --> 00:43:05.820
to ask and things like that,
but the intention, at least,

00:43:05.820 --> 00:43:08.145
early on, was never for it
to be a super polished, hey,

00:43:08.145 --> 00:43:09.686
make sure to mention
how you're going

00:43:09.686 --> 00:43:11.510
to use the profits from
your business for education,

00:43:11.510 --> 00:43:12.584
because people love that.

00:43:12.584 --> 00:43:14.500
And it's not like, oh,
that's a great picture,

00:43:14.500 --> 00:43:15.556
but can you have
your kid in there,

00:43:15.556 --> 00:43:16.880
because people love kids?

00:43:16.880 --> 00:43:19.340
Right?

00:43:19.340 --> 00:43:21.820
I'm so guilty of it myself.

00:43:21.820 --> 00:43:23.830
So anyway, that's
sort of, I think,

00:43:23.830 --> 00:43:27.120
the ethos-- that's the
spirit of how Kiva operates.

00:43:27.120 --> 00:43:30.340
In terms of what I personally
think makes a good story.

00:43:30.340 --> 00:43:36.040
I mean, I think transparency
and balancing-- I don't know,

00:43:36.040 --> 00:43:41.330
I mean, I think
being as personal

00:43:41.330 --> 00:43:46.087
and is honest about what you're
going through, as you can,

00:43:46.087 --> 00:43:47.170
is kind of all you can do.

00:43:47.170 --> 00:43:49.086
And that usually resonates
the most of people.

00:43:49.086 --> 00:43:50.730
I think people
want to be let in.

00:43:50.730 --> 00:43:54.202
In kind of the inner
circle, and to feel like

00:43:54.202 --> 00:43:56.410
they're really participating
and really a part of it.

00:43:56.410 --> 00:43:59.531
Some of the-- who asked the
challenges question back there,

00:43:59.531 --> 00:44:00.030
yeah.

00:44:00.030 --> 00:44:01.655
So some of the more
challenging moments

00:44:01.655 --> 00:44:04.660
when we've had to talk about,
oh, sorry, your money is not

00:44:04.660 --> 00:44:07.620
coming back, because this field
partner did something terrible.

00:44:07.620 --> 00:44:09.620
Which is few and far
between, but it's happened.

00:44:09.620 --> 00:44:11.320
I remember being
terrified, the first time,

00:44:11.320 --> 00:44:12.820
to put that story out
there into the world,

00:44:12.820 --> 00:44:14.670
and explain to people
what had happened.

00:44:14.670 --> 00:44:16.470
But the transparency
of it, I mean,

00:44:16.470 --> 00:44:18.426
we didn't get an angry
email or note back.

00:44:18.426 --> 00:44:20.300
People were like, thanks
for being so honest,

00:44:20.300 --> 00:44:22.315
this is really hard
work to do, we get it.

00:44:22.315 --> 00:44:23.940
We're going to re-lend
anyway, or we're

00:44:23.940 --> 00:44:25.000
going to lend new
money, because we're not

00:44:25.000 --> 00:44:26.310
getting our money back.

00:44:26.310 --> 00:44:29.810
But they were very supportive
and appreciated, I think,

00:44:29.810 --> 00:44:33.510
being in the trenches with
us, and on the ground,

00:44:33.510 --> 00:44:35.466
and hearing the honest stuff.

00:44:35.466 --> 00:44:36.438
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

